Nice — moving Keycloak to Kubernetes is exactly the right next step 👍
Let’s do this cleanly and **production-friendly**, while keeping everything in **one YAML file** like you asked.

---

# 🧱 What We’ll Create (Single YAML)

We’ll include:

1. **Namespace** (optional but clean)
2. **Deployment** (Keycloak container)
3. **Service** (ClusterIP → internal access)
4. **Ingress** (external access URL)

---

# 📦 ✅ Full Kubernetes YAML (Single File)

You can save this as:

```bash
keycloak-all.yaml
```

```yaml
apiVersion: v1
kind: Namespace
metadata:
  name: keycloak

---
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: keycloak
  namespace: keycloak
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: keycloak
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: keycloak
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: keycloak
          image: quay.io/keycloak/keycloak:24.0.2
          args: ["start-dev"]
          ports:
            - containerPort: 8080
          env:
            - name: KEYCLOAK_ADMIN
              value: admin
            - name: KEYCLOAK_ADMIN_PASSWORD
              value: admin
            - name: KC_PROXY
              value: edge
            - name: KC_HOSTNAME
              value: keycloak.local
            - name: KC_HOSTNAME_STRICT
              value: "false"

---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: keycloak
  namespace: keycloak
spec:
  type: ClusterIP
  selector:
    app: keycloak
  ports:
    - port: 80
      targetPort: 8080

---
apiVersion: networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: Ingress
metadata:
  name: keycloak
  namespace: keycloak
  annotations:
    nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/rewrite-target: /
spec:
  ingressClassName: nginx
  rules:
    - host: keycloak.local
      http:
        paths:
          - path: /
            pathType: Prefix
            backend:
              service:
                name: keycloak
                port:
                  number: 80
```

---

# 🚀 Apply It

```bash
kubectl apply -f keycloak-all.yaml
```

---

# 🌐 How to Access Keycloak (VERY IMPORTANT)

## ✅ Your Keycloak URL will be:

```
http://keycloak.local
```

---

## 🛠 But you MUST add this to your machine:

Edit your hosts file:

### Mac / Linux:

```bash
sudo nano /etc/hosts
```

### Windows:

```
C:\Windows\System32\drivers\etc\hosts
```

Add:

```
127.0.0.1 keycloak.local
```

---

# ⚠️ Important Requirements

## 1. You need an Ingress Controller

If you don’t already have one:

Install NGINX ingress:

```bash
kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kubernetes/ingress-nginx/main/deploy/static/provider/cloud/deploy.yaml
```

---

## 2. Check everything is running

```bash
kubectl get pods -n keycloak
kubectl get svc -n keycloak
kubectl get ingress -n keycloak
```

---

# 🔐 Keycloak Admin Access

Once it’s up:

👉 Open:

```
http://keycloak.local
```

Login:

* username: `admin`
* password: `admin`

---

# 🔥 Integration Tip (VERY important for your project)

In your **Arthur Core config**, use:

```
issuer: http://keycloak.local/realms/<your-realm>
```

NOT localhost anymore.

---

# ⚠️ If It Doesn’t Work

Check:

```bash
kubectl describe ingress keycloak -n keycloak
kubectl logs -n keycloak deployment/keycloak
```

